<section xml:id="sec-Data-handling" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Data handling</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Meaning-of-data">
    <title>Meaning of data</title>
       <p>
           Data is a collection of facts such as numbers and measurements that we learn, make decisions or solve problems.
       </p> 
        <p>
            An example of data in a market could be the information collected about what customers buy and how much they spend. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Moraa owns a fruit stall, and she records the following information for one day:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Customer Names: Ekadeli, Mbasu, Baya</li>
            <li>Items Bought: Apples, Bananas, Oranges</li>
            <li>Quantity: 5 apples, 3 bananas, 2 oranges</li>
            <li>Price Paid: Ksh250, ksh100, ksh150</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            This information is data because it tells you what your customers bought, how much they bought, and how much they spent.
            You could use this data to figure out things like:
            <ul>
                <li>Which fruit was bought the most?</li>
                <li>How much money you earned in a day.</li>
                <li>What to stock more of next time to meet demand.</li>   
            </ul>
        </p>
       <p>
           This is how data helps businesses make decisions.
       </p>
    <activity> 
        <p>
            Work in groups
        </p>
        <p>
                (i) Each learner state their understanding of the term data.
      </p>
            <p>
                (ii) Search for the meaning of data from different sources.
            </p>
            <p>
                (iii) Discuss and compare with other groups.
            </p>

    </activity>
    
  </subsection>

   <p>
    Learning point
   </p>
   <p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
              Data is a collection of facts such as numbers and measurements collected to represent information.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ul>
   </p>
   <subsection xml:id="subsec-Collection-of-data">
    <title>Collection of data</title>
    <p>
        A collection of data refers to the process of gathering and assembling relevant pieces of information or facts from various sources for analysis or use.
    </p>
    <p>
        This data can be quantitative (numerical) or qualitative (descriptive) and is typically organized in a structured manner to allow for efficient examination or decision-making.
    </p> 
    <p>
        Data collection can take many forms, such as:
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>Surveys and questionnaires: Gathering responses from individuals</li>
        <li>Experiments: Recording observations or measurements during controlled experiments.</li>
        <li>Interviews: Collecting qualitative data through direct interactions.</li>
    </ol>
    <activity>
   <p>
    Work in groups
   </p> 
    <p>
        (i) Collect data on the number of classrooms in your school.
    </p>
    <p>
       (ii) Count the number of textbooks for each subject in your class. 
    </p>
    <p>
        (iii) Collect data on the number of male and female in your class.
    </p> 
    <p>
        (iv) Collect information on the number of left handed students in your class.
    </p>
    <p>
        (v) Discuss and compare with other groups.
    </p>
   </activity>
    
   </subsection>
   
   <p>
    Learning point
   </p>
   <ul>
    <li>
        <p>
           Data collected from different situations vary from each other. 
        </p>
    </li>
   </ul>
   
